Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 67th Weekly Dose of Optimism.
It=E2=80=99s a big weekend here in NYC =E2=80=94 Marathon weekend. I like t=
o think of marathons as optimistic endeavors =E2=80=94 displaying human pot=
ential, our ability to overcome obstacles, and to delay instant gratificati=
on in favor of longer-term personal growth. You don=E2=80=99t meet too many=
 pessimistic marathon runners. Good luck to all runners this weekend, with =
a special s/o to my girlfriend Sienna =E2=9D=A4=EF=B8=8F.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Age of Miracles [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/f0fd9df2-cab9-4d96-b915-fd3d173b7609?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy here. Instead of a sponsor, I=E2=80=99m going to pump our new podcast=
: Age of Miracles. Our first season is on nuclear energy, and the combinati=
on of innovation and nitty gritty it=E2=80=99s going to take to build an en=
ergy abundant future. We just released Episode 3 minutes ago. =20
You can listen to it on Apple [ https://substack.com/redirect/379df901-ecb5=
-4679-97bb-49c48f1e0f12?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Spotify [ https://substack.com/redirect/ffdc16b0-36c6-4b=
b9-8d4c-ec602377c253?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ], or wherever you listen to podcasts, or watch it on YouTube =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/d715026c-1994-4afc-a7e2-33a9e4c75a94?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Thanks to all of you who listened, commented, liked, subscribed, reviewed, =
shared, and gave us feedback on our first two episodes! We climbed as high =
as #12 on the top tech podcast charts, which beat my expectations for Week =
1. Let=E2=80=99s keep it going and break the top 10.
Episode three is all about what it=E2=80=99s going to take to build more la=
rge reactors more affordably and predictably. We cover how nuclear plants w=
ork, their economics, why their Idiot Index is so high, and the steps we mi=
ght take to improve their economics. We cover everything from cost overrun =
insurance to psyops, debate whether government or the free market has a big=
ger role to play, and try to answer the question of what it would take to b=
ring large nuclear plants down the experience curve.=20
For those who want to go deeper, we put together a Nuclear Resource Guide [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/16cd0398-bbba-4d97-be61-f8097cc37bff?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that we=E2=80=
=99re updating each episode, with links to articles, podcasts, videos, and =
more.=20
I want to give a big shoutout and congrats to my co-host, Julia DeWahl [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/489073cd-621b-4d5a-815b-07606db7c08b?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. The company she=
 co-founded, Antares [ https://substack.com/redirect/8f0059ad-3526-4fa6-ac1=
3-6fea57dbb394?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ], came out of stealth and announced an $8 million seed this week. T=
heir vision: abundant clean energy for all, from earth to the asteroid belt=
=2E You=E2=80=99ll hear a little more a=
bout what they=E2=80=99re building on=20=
Episode 5.
(1) World's smallest particle accelerator is 54 million times smaller than =
the Large Hadron Collider =E2=80=94 and it works [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/a931ac34-1d96-4b4b-9a64-8dc75fe5edfa?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Harry Baker for Space.com
"The dream application would be to place a particle accelerator on an endos=
cope in order to be able to administer radiotherapy directly at the affecte=
d area within the body,"
OK, you probably didn=E2=80=99t expect Mini-Me humping a laser to start off=
 the newsletter, but let me explain=E2=80=A6Scientists have activated the w=
orld's smallest particle accelerator, a nanophotonic electron accelerator (=
NEA), which is the size of a coin and accelerates electrons using mini lase=
r beams aimed at "pillars" within a microchip. Anytime I hear mini and lase=
rs in the same sentence, my mind goes to the image above=E2=80=A6sue me.
The NEA is 54 million time smaller than the 16.8-mile-long Large Hadron Col=
lider at CERN. It fits within a microchip and boasts a main acceleration tu=
be only 0.02 inches long.
The NEA has wide range of potential applications, including putting particl=
e accelerators inside human patients. For example, a tiny NEA could be plac=
ed on an endoscope to better administer precise radiotherapy for cancer pat=
ients. That=E2=80=99s the main goal of the research, but who knows what els=
e those crazy scientists will dream up once we have the ability to put part=
icle accelerators inside of humans. Accelerate, indeed.=20
(2) This Pulsing DNA Nanomotor Can Power Molecular Machines [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/22bc74af-0e7a-4136-9bdd-a6be618a29b2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Prachi Patel for IEEE Spectrum
Famulok=E2=80=99s vision is to use the pulsing nanomotor to drive several D=
NA origami machines =E2=80=9Cin a sort of molecular assembly line=E2=80=9D =
that could build complex chemicals such as artificial proteins, or drive ch=
emical reactions that are otherwise difficult to achieve.
Speaking of tiny machines inside of our body=E2=80=A6 an international team=
 of researchers have developed a DNA nanoengine that can perform pulsing mo=
vements, driving nanomaters with chemical energy instead of random Brownian=
 motion. It=E2=80=99s an example of DNA origami, which =E2=80=9Cinvolves ca=
refully designing DNA sequences that can fold, twist, and staple together a=
t the right places to assemble into preconceived structures.=E2=80=9D
On Tuesday, Elliot [ https://substack.com/redirect/c01bfb0d-54d2-495b-b091-=
9b6c519fcc2b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ] took us on a tour of the mindblowing world of cell-based therapy [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/0f2c0c16-764b-4259-bb18-6a07ce3394a4?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. He wrote about=
 =E2=80=9Cengineering a patient=E2=80=99s own immune cells to cure cancer, =
reprogramming cells and tissues to a younger and healthier state as we age,=
 designing bacteria in our gut to pump out GLP-1 molecules when we eat too =
much, and curing diabetes with a single infusion of cells instead of countl=
ess infusions of insulin.=E2=80=9D
DNA nanomachines are another avenue for making changes inside our body, and=
 in the physical world. The researchers think that their pulsing nanometer =
should be easy to connect to other tiny molecular machines, driving them as=
 they construct medicines and electronics [ https://substack.com/redirect/0=
b4c83cd-d35d-4912-8151-12a29b5f3177?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
DNA origami nanoengines that can make things =E2=80=A6 what a world.=20
(3) First plasma fired up at world=E2=80=99s largest fusion reactor [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/b276b7c8-4fe8-452f-865e-2872bbfd3ef8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Dennis Normile for Science
The long trek toward practical fusion energy passed a milestone last week w=
hen the world=E2=80=99s newest and largest fusion reactor fired up. Japan=
=E2=80=99s JT-60SA uses magnetic fields from superconducting coils to conta=
in a blazingly hot cloud of ionized gas, or plasma, within a doughnut-shape=
d vacuum vessel, in hope of coaxing hydrogen nuclei to fuse and release ene=
rgy. The four-story-high machine is designed to hold a plasma heated to 200=
 million degrees Celsius for about 100 seconds, far longer than previous la=
rge tokamaks.
Big things are happening at much larger scales, too. We=E2=80=99re one smal=
l step closer to commercial fusion.=20
Japan's JT-60SA, the world's largest fusion reactor, turned on last week. T=
his machine can sustain a plasma heated to 200 million degrees Celsius for =
about 100 seconds, surpassing prior large tokamaks. The activation demonstr=
ates the reactor's foundational functionality, though it will take another =
couple of years before the JT-60SA can sustain plasmas long enough for use =
in meaningful physics experiments.=20
That said, the success of and learnings from JT-60SA will bolster the progr=
ess of ITER, the world's largest and most advanced experimental tokamak rea=
ctor. The main goal of ITER is to demonstrate the feasibility of large scal=
e fusion. While ITER is based in France, it=E2=80=99s one of the largest  i=
nternational scientific collaborations in history, with over 35 countries i=
nvolved, including the US, China, and Russia.=20
Both ITER and JT-60SA have been slow =E2=80=94 with such advanced, complex,=
 and enormous machines, there are bound to be issues and delays =E2=80=94 a=
nd we=E2=80=99re excited by the startups entering the Fusion Race [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/fc6c7aed-f792-4f56-bc67-2d6025653de2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to speed things up. B=
ut fusion is a great demonstration of the interplay between government, aca=
demia, and startups, across the world, working together to unlock abundant =
energy for all of humanity.=20
The more that reactors like JT-60SA push progress and knowledge forward, th=
e faster others in the space can move, and the closer we get to generating =
power the same way the sun does.=20
(4) Regulating AI by Executive Order is the Real AI Risk [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/3d54d6f4-8527-410f-9c5=
d-3daf6670f201?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Steven Sinofsky for Hardcore Engineering
The President=E2=80=99s Executive Order on Artificial Intelligence is a pre=
mature and pessimistic political solution to unknown technical problems and=
 a clear case of regulatory capture at a time when the world would be best =
served by optimism and innovation.
On Monday, The White House issued an Executive Order on the Safe, Secure, a=
nd Trustworthy Development and Use of Artificial Intelligence [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/13ff27eb-f241-4dd7-83bd-a50a0d301f42?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. It=E2=80=99s still TBD h=
ow the EO will play out in practice, but it is clear that the Federal Gover=
nment is  paying more attention to AI and that tighter regulation will like=
ly follow. What would be a win for the leading AI companies of today =E2=80=
=94 whatever risk-mitigating regulation that flows from this EO will likely=
 only go to further entrenched companies like Microsoft, Google, and OpenAI=
, and stifle innovation and ambition from current and future AI startups.=
=20
That=E2=80=99s the argument Ben Thompson makes in the most fiery Stratecher=
y piece we=E2=80=99ve read in a long time: Attenuating Innovation [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/4bf9d333-e42a-4274-9e29-dc8cffa2c16e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:=20
The point is this: if you accept the premise that regulation locks in incum=
bents, then it sure is notable that the early AI winners seem the most inve=
sted in generating alarm in Washington, D.C. about AI. This despite the fac=
t that their concern is apparently not sufficiently high to, you know, stop=
 their work. No, they are the responsible ones, the ones who care enough to=
 call for regulation; all the better if concerns about imagined harms kneec=
ap inevitable competitors.
Steven Sinofsky [ https://substack.com/redirect/2eefc4bd-3b3f-416c-b5e2-53a=
ac237cd2c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ], a former president of the Windows Division at Microsoft and current Bo=
ard Partner at a16z, predicts a similar outcome in the essay linked above. =
The main point of Sinofsky=E2=80=99s essay is that this EO seems to be comi=
ng from a place of fear and pessimism =E2=80=94 if you think that AI is goi=
ng to destroy the world, you=E2=80=99d try to regulate it =E2=80=94 rather =
than a place of optimism. Pessimism, in this case, will ultimately lead to =
regulatory capture and stifled innovation. Optimistic law making would prom=
ote research, competition, and experimentation to push U.S.-based companies=
 to the frontier of A.I. and ensure the nation is at the cutting edge of th=
is technological wave.
Optimism (and pessimism) shape reality. This is a prime example of that.=20
Once a regulation is in place, it=E2=80=99s incredibly hard to roll it back=
=2E Thankfully, this is just an Executi=
ve Order, but it should be a warning s=
hot that we=E2=80=99re going to put rules in place now that could impact hu=
manity for decades to come. It=E2=80=99s worth reading both Sinofsky and Th=
ompson=E2=80=99s pieces to get up to speed and fight on the side of the opt=
imists.=20
(5) Palmer Luckey - Inventing the Future of Defense [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/0ec668fb-ef8f-445f-baf6-3d2da64b70ef?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
If I could boil it down to one principle. I know my Facebook About Page has=
 said for over 10 years, making the world a different place. The point ther=
e is, obviously, I want the world to be better.
I don't want to make changes that are for the worst. But I'd say more than =
setting out to say, I want to make the world somewhat better. It's that I w=
ant to have a big impact on the world. And of course, I try to orient that =
in a way that I think is to positive ends, but I don't want to do something=
 that doesn't matter.
Packy here. If there=E2=80=99s anybody who has hands-on experience actually=
 putting AI in weapons systems, it=E2=80=99s Palmer Luckey [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/79b96fdd-426b-4a90-9249-aa8c06367bb2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], the founder of Oculus and A=
nduril. And Palmer thinks AGI, if we achieve it, will be more useful on def=
ense than offense.=20
I am not scared of AGI the way that a lot of people are. I think that AGI i=
s a technology where the benefits do accrue more to the defender than on th=
e offensive side.
Obviously, people can pick examples here and there, "Aw, but here's this ho=
rrible thing that it could be used for." I still think the benefits actuall=
y accrue more to the defender=E2=80=A6=20
In other words, if AGI is so good that it can come up with anthrax two and =
it's just an incredibly powerful thing, I would hope that AGI can also come=
 up with a thing that immunizes people against it or that builds nanobots t=
hat are in our blood stream at all times that are able to, on the fly, comp=
ute exactly what they're going to do to stop any biological threat, natural=
 or man-made. It's a case where the defensive uses like that are actually g=
oing to outweigh the offensive uses in the long run.
That=E2=80=99s just one of the many gems in Palmer=E2=80=99s conversation w=
ith Patrick O=E2=80=99Shaughnessy [ http://if I could boil it down to one p=
rinciple. I know my Facebook About Page has said for over 10 years, making =
the world a different place. The point there is, obviously, I want the worl=
d to be better.     I don't want to make changes that are for the worst. Bu=
t I'd say more than setting out to say, I want to make the world somewhat b=
etter. It's that I want to have a big impact on the world. And of course, I=
 try to orient that in a way that I think is to positive ends, but I don't =
want to do something that doesn't matter. ] on Invest Like the Best.=20
In recent years, he=E2=80=99s used the podcast circuit to go scorched-earth=
 on the investors, partners, and journalists that he believes mistreated hi=
m earlier in his career. You should go find those podcasts, like this appea=
rance at the All-In Summit [ https://substack.com/redirect/b75ffd3d-be62-46=
03-8580-020a5326ff82?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ], because they are both entertaining and eye-opening as to ho=
w tech media operates. This conversation was much different.
In this one, Palmer describes his motivations for doing what we he does: to=
 make the world a different place. He wants to make it better, certainly, b=
ut above all else, he wants to make a big impact. And to do that, he builds=
 big companies.=20
Palmer Luckey is a singular character. Chances are, you won=E2=80=99t be ab=
le to listen to this podcast, download his wisdom, and go out and do what h=
e does.=20
But it=E2=80=99s one of the best podcast conversations I=E2=80=99ve heard i=
n a long time because it highlights the balance of ambition, innovation, an=
d practicality that=E2=80=99s necessary to make big things happen. I=E2=80=
=99m not going to start the next Anduril, but listening to the conversation=
 certainly made me think about what I am trying to accomplish with what I h=
ave.=20
I=E2=80=99m happy we have people like Palmer Luckey working on the side of =
the good guys.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tu=
esday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

